The '''''Dresden'' class''' was a pair of [[light cruiser]]s built for the [[Imperial German Navy]] in the early part of the 20th century. The class comprised {{SMS|Dresden|1907|6}}, the [[lead ship]], and {{SMS|Emden|1906|6}}. Both ships were laid down in 1906; ''Dresden'' was launched in 1907, and ''Emden'' followed in 1908. They entered service in 1908 and 1909, respectively. The design for the ships was an incremental improvement over the preceding [[Königsberg class cruiser (1905)|''Königsberg'' class]], being slightly larger and slightly faster, but with the same primary armament of ten {{convert|10.5|cm|abbr=on}} guns. ''Dresden'' and ''Emden'' were powered by [[steam turbine]]s and [[triple expansion engine]]s, respectively, as part of continued experiments with the new turbine technology.

Both ships served extensively on foreign stations; ''Emden'' was assigned to the [[German East Asia Squadron|East Asia Squadron]] from her commissioning, and ''Dresden'' was sent to Caribbean waters in 1913. ''Dresden'' was due to return to Germany for periodic maintenance shortly before the outbreak of [[World War I]] in August 1914, but this became impossible with the onset of hostilities. She therefore operated as a commerce raider, before linking up with ''[[Vizeadmiral]]'' [[Maximilian von Spee]]'s East Asia Squadron. ''Dresden'' thereafter participated in the [[Battle of Coronel]] in November 1914 and the [[Battle of the Falkland Islands]] the following December. She was the only German vessel to escape destruction at the latter engagement, and she remained at large for several more months. ''Dresden'' finally put into the Chilean island of [[Robinson Crusoe Island|Más a Tierra]] in March 1915 owing to worn-out engines. A pair of British cruisers violated Chilean neutrality and attacked ''Dresden'' while she lay at anchor; the Germans scuttled their ship to prevent her capture.

''Emden'', meanwhile, had been detached from the East Asia Squadron to pursue an independent commerce raiding campaign in the Indian Ocean. She captured or sank numerous [[Triple Entente|Entente]] vessels, including the steamer [[SMS Cormoran (1909)|''Ryazan'']], which was converted into the [[auxiliary cruiser]] ''Cormoran''. In September 1914, ''Emden'' raided [[Penang]] and caught the Russian [[protected cruiser]] [[Russian cruiser Zhemchug|''Zhemchug'']] and the French [[destroyer]] [[French destroyer Mousquet|''Mousquet'']] and quickly destroyed both ships. Shortly thereafter, ''Emden'' was caught by the Australian cruiser {{HMAS|Sydney|1912|6}} off the [[Cocos Islands]] and forced to beach after a ferocious engagement.

==Design==
The two ships of the ''Dresden'' class were ordered in the 1905&ndash;1906 construction program. Their design represents an incremental improvement over the earlier [[Königsberg class cruiser (1905)|''Königsberg'' class]]. They carried the same main battery of {{convert|10.5|cm|abbr=on}} guns on a slightly greater [[Displacement (ship)|displacement]]. Like the ''Königsberg''s, one ship&mdash;''Dresden''&mdash;was fitted with a [[steam turbine]] engine to compare its performance with the traditional [[triple-expansion engine]] in an otherwise-identical [[sister ship]].<ref name=GG157/> All subsequent designs of German cruisers utilized turbine propulsion systems.<ref>Gardiner & Gray, pp. 159&ndash;163</ref>

===General characteristics===
[[File:Dresden class cruiser diagrams Janes 1914.jpg|thumb|left|<center>Left elevation and deck plan as depicted in [[Jane's Fighting Ships]] 1914</center>]]

The two ''Dresden''-class cruisers were {{convert|117.90|m|ftin|sp=us}} [[length at the waterline|long at the waterline]] and {{convert|118.30|m|ftin|abbr=on}} [[length overall|long overall]]. They had a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|13.50|m|ftin|abbr=on}} and a [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|5.53|m|ftin|abbr=on}} forward. They displaced {{convert|3664|t|LT|LT|sp=us}} as designed and up to {{convert|4268|t|LT|LT|sp=us|abbr=on}} at full combat load. Their hulls were constructed with transverse and longitudinal steel frames. The hulls contained thirteen [[watertight compartment]]s and had a [[double bottom]] that extended for 47&nbsp;percent of the length of the [[keel]].<ref name=G105>Gröner, p. 105</ref>

The ships were good sea boats, but they were [[:wikt:crank|crank]] and rolled up to twenty degrees. They were also very wet at high speeds and suffered from a slight [[weather helm]]. Nevertheless, the ships turned tightly and were very maneuverable. In a hard turn, their speed fell up to 35&nbsp;percent. They had a transverse [[metacentric height]] of {{convert|.59|m|ftin|abbr=on}}. ''Dresden'' and ''Emden'' had a crew of 18&nbsp;officers and 343&nbsp;enlisted men. They carried a number of smaller boats, including one [[picket boat]], one barge, one [[Cutter (boat)|cutter]], two [[yawl]]s, and two [[dinghy|dinghies]].<ref name=G105/>

===Machinery===
''Dresden''{{'}}s propulsion system consisted of two [[Parsons Marine Steam Turbine Company|Parsons]] steam turbines, designed to give {{convert|15000|shp|kW|lk=on|0}}. ''Emden'', instead, was equipped with two triple expansion engines rated at {{convert|13500|ihp|kW|lk=on|0}}. Both ships had a top speed of {{convert|24|kn|lk=in}}. In both vessels, the engines were powered by twelve coal-fired Marine-type [[water-tube boiler]]s. Both ships carried up to {{convert|860|MT|LT}} of coal, though their ranges were slightly different, owing to their different propulsion systems. ''Dresden'' could steam for {{convert|3600|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|14|kn}}, while ''Emden'' had a range of {{convert|3760|nmi|abbr=on}} at {{convert|12|kn}}. Electrical power was supplied by three [[turbo-generator]]s that provided a total of 125&nbsp;[[kilowatt]]s at 110&nbsp;[[volt]]s.<ref name=G105/>

===Armament and armor===
[[File:Emden-gun-3.jpg|thumb|One of ''Emden''{{'}}s 10.5&nbsp;cm guns, preserved in [[Sydney, Australia]]]]

The ships were armed with ten [[10.5 cm SK L/40 naval gun|10.5&nbsp;cm SK L/40 guns]] in single pedestal mounts. Two were placed side by side forward on the [[forecastle]], six were located amidships, three on either side, and two were side by side aft.<ref name=GG157>Gardiner & Gray, p. 157</ref> The guns had a maximum elevation of 30&nbsp;degrees, which allowed them to engage targets out to {{convert|12700|m|yd|abbr=on}}.<ref>Gardiner & Gray, p. 140</ref> They were supplied with 1,500 rounds of ammunition, for 150 shells per gun. The ships were also equipped with eight [[5.2 cm SK L/55 naval gun|5.2 cm SK L/55]] guns with 4,000 rounds of ammunition. Both ships were also equipped with a pair of {{convert|45|cm|abbr=on}} [[torpedo tube]]s with five [[torpedo]]es submerged in the hull on the [[broadside]].<ref name=G105/>

The ships were protected by an armored deck that was up to {{convert|80|mm|abbr=on}} thick amidships with {{convert|50|mm|abbr=on}} thick sloping armor on the sides. The deck was reduced to {{convert|30|mm|abbr=on}} further aft and then again to {{convert|20|mm|abbr=on}} toward the stern. The [[conning tower]] had {{convert|100|mm|abbr=on}} thick sides, and the guns were protected by 50&nbsp;mm thick shields.<ref name=G105/>

